SQL-03
Company Boss — Self Join
Medium
Table: employees
id | name | manager_id | salary ---|---------|------------|------- 1 | Big Boss| NULL | 200000 2 | Alice | 1 | 90000 3 | Bob | 1 | 85000 4 | Carol | 2 | 70000 5 | Dan | 2 | 65000
Problem
Show each employee with their manager's name. The top boss has no manager. Also find employees who earn more than their manager.
Solution
-- Part 1: Employee with their manager name
SELECT
    e.name AS employee_name,
    e.salary AS employee_salary,
    COALESCE(m.name, 'Top Boss') AS manager_name,
    m.salary AS manager_salary
FROM employees e
LEFT JOIN employees m ON e.manager_id = m.id
ORDER BY e.id;

-- Part 2: Employees earning MORE than their manager
SELECT
    e.name AS employee,
    e.salary AS emp_salary,
    m.name AS manager,
    m.salary AS mgr_salary
FROM employees e
JOIN employees m ON e.manager_id = m.id
WHERE e.salary > m.salary;
Self Join: Join the table to itself using two aliases (e = employee, m = manager). Match e.manager_id = m.id. Use LEFT JOIN so the top boss (NULL manager_id) still appears. COALESCE(m.name, 'Top Boss') handles the NULL case cleanly.